# DC VAMC, Oct 23 2024

* ~22 new verified accounts (these notes only include a subset of these experiences)
  * Including several folks who’d previously tried on their own, and many who at least knew it was coming, and some who were completely unaware, at least 2 who’d never signed in online before.  
* 6 veterans already with modern account who needed some help (like a password reset)  
  * One veteran I helped, we went to Login.gov to set up new account, but they already had email registered \- I helped reset password and everything was good to go (even verify had already been complete)  
  * One veteran I helped thought they had set up an ID.me at some point, but the password didn't work. Helped reset the password and he was good to go.  
* 2 unsuccessful attempts to verify (1 due to phone giving “out of memory” error on ID upload step plus needing to get to an appointment before we could finish)

## Observations about veterans we talked with

* A couple veterans expressed displeasure about the change  
* Several had to be talked through to understand that MHV isn’t going away, just the sign in process is changing  
* Most veterans were very friendly and caring. A couple seemed to just enjoy having someone to talk with.  
* Most were accepting of the sign in change, but wanted to be told what to do.  
  * I always first asked if they had a modern CSP and if not if they had a preference.  
  * I simply explained LIG is government and the IDme a private company. None of the veterans I helped had a preference, they just wanted to be told what to do. So I tended to start with LIG if there was no other indication  
* Some already had a modern credential but never used it or were locked out  
* Most were free with their PII and PHI, they weren’t worried who had it, and **additional account security wasn’t a major concern for them**  
  * For example, one veteran asked me to type a message to her doctor while we were in her account  
  * Almost every one we helped wrote down their password  
  * One veteran prefered for me to type in their password and social security number when it came to those steps  
  * Some veterans seemed stressed by needing a 12 character password on LIG, but on the other hand they were pleasantly surprised to not need a required amount of cap, nums, or symbols there.  
* Some veterans preferred to drive the process, seeking help at various points, others preferred to have us drive, even handling their phone for the ID verification step  
  * One veteran I helped had limited mobility in her left arm and pain in her right shoulder. She had trouble navigating between laptop and phone, and preferred I took over both.  
    * It was eye opening to see the struggle and effort if took for her to simply pull up a text on her phone (like for MFA)

## Process issues and observations

* Lots of app switches and device switches during the verify process that gave trouble to older, less technology included veterans \- they would have struggled or not been able to complete this without our help  
  * Moving to phone and then back for ID images.  
  * Understanding when they need to check text vs email  
  * Lots of scroll esp on phone, but also on laptop \- "continue" button at many steps was below the fold (both LIG and IDme). **Veterans who I had drive the process were often not sure what to do next, and needed me to point out the button or to scroll to find the button to go to the next step.**  
  * Another volunteer had a video verify session that was hard for the older veteran \- on the phone and was asked to use the back facing camera  
  * **One international veteran couldn't add text MFA** (due to having a VOIP number), but was ok with a code generator app. This one also couldn't verify his foreign address, but was able to ID verify via IDme phone call  
  * **There are a ton of sign ins (and MFAs) through the process of setting up and verifying an account.** We know sign in can be a struggle for some veterans, so setting up a new account is a huge barrier for some folks.

    

* **We saw several errors throughout the day that caused confusion**, even if they didn’t completely stop the process.  
  * Specifically when linking CSP to VA, an error can come up that makes it seem like the process failed \- but it just required signing back in  
    * it happened for sure on Login.gov, and I know that it happened at least 4 times throughout the day  
        
  * This Sign In Error, I forgot the context. But similar to the other, signing back into the CSP for VA seemed to work.  
    ![][image1]  
* On the ID.me ID verify step, one veteran’s phone crashed twice. I then created a Login.gov account, but on the ID verify step the same thing happened. I saw this time there was an “out of memory” warning so the device couldn’t handle the task.  
  * We ran out of time, since he had an appointment to get to.  
  * Note also tried to send images to my computer but couldn't get airplay to work (using a different user profile today vs my main work sign in). We decided to try ID.me video call if we had any more issues.  
* One veteran had an ID.me, but needed to set up MFA \- no problem there.  
  * On the ID image step it wouldn't accept the ID pictures. Tried 3 times.   
  * Veteran was going to an appointment so when they came back, we finished verification with a video call  
* **Several times on the video call, ID.me representative said they should get 2 emails and the veteran didn’t (at least in the short amount of time before they left).**  
  * They still had access to their account, but it made for an unsettling CX experience to tell people to look out for an email that doesn’t come  
* Verifying a veteran on Login.gov and first shot at the ID image failed  
  * This is when we started using a “shadow box” to help keep glare off the ID when taking an image.

## Other thoughts

* I personally liked the Login.gov ID verification step better \- it seemed there were things to click and/or fewer pages to click through. The veterans I helped who were driving the process seemed to have an easier time with that than on ID.me  
  * I did try to allow veterans to drive the process to help them feel more empowered, but many did prefer I just did all the clicking through and even typing  
* Other volunteers were starting with ID.me  
* Each service has different password requirements, which might help veterans decide which service to choose, to the effect they want to  
  * LIG requires a longer PW 12 characters vs IDme 8  
  * IDme requires Cap, nums, and symbols, where LIG is agnostic  
* ID.me had the superior process if there were issues with ID documents, the ability to do the video chat allowed us to finish setting up without directing them to a USPS location  
  * BUT the ID.me page to set up a video verification, the page for submitting documents is confusing
